Why: the per-device dma-coherent pool allocator (bitmap_find_free_region)
rounds every allocation up to a power-of-2 page order and places it
order-aligned, so an allocation can occupy up to ~2x its size and the pool
returns ENOMEM well below its nominal capacity. Replaced with page-granular
first-fit (bitmap_find_next_zero_area); a per-allocation page-count map lets
the release path free the exact count instead of relying on the caller's
get_order(size). wave5 and ml_mmzheap (the userspace mmz dma-heap) share the
single rmem coherent pool on this system.

Also adds a read-only debugfs view per rmem-backed pool
(/sys/kernel/debug/dma_coherent/<rmem-name>): base, page counts used/free,
the largest free run, and the live allocation list. The shared pool was a
black box (only indirect tenant-side tallies existed), which made every
ENOMEM/fragmentation question a live experiment.

Caveat: this drops the DMA-API natural-alignment guarantee (smallest
power-of-2 order >= size) for EVERY per-device coherent pool, deliberately:
order-aligned placement is where the waste comes from, and neither pool
tenant (wave5, ml_mmzheap) masks address bits. Any future driver with a
per-device pool whose hardware requires naturally-aligned buffers
(address-bit-masked descriptor rings) must not rely on dma_alloc_coherent
alignment under this patch.

